The Voice of Conscience

Jallianwala Bagh massacre: The horror of survivors
1919
Narayan Vinayak Virkar
(Photographer)
TOI take:
Published on: Mar 12, 2025
This 1919 photograph captures witnesses of the Jallianwala Bagh massacre, with bullet holes circled in white as survivors point to them. British troops, under General Dyer, killed hundreds of peaceful protesters. While Dyer tried to silence dissent, this image became a powerful voice against British colonial atrocities.
Thailand's darkest hour
1976
Neal Ulevich
(Photographer)
TOI take:
Published on: Mar 05, 2025
This image from Thammasat University massacre (October 6, 1976) shows a man swinging a chair at the hanged body of a student while a crowd watches, some smiling. Though often censored, the lynching of student activists by right- wing extremists fueled Thailand’s struggle for democracy, inspiring future protests and reforms.
Lifesaving marathon
1987
James Stanfield
(Photographer)
TOI take:
Published on: Feb 27, 2025
This 1987 photo captures Dr Zbigniew Religa after a 23-hour heart transplant, watching over his patient while his colleague sleeps in the corner. Despite the surgery seeming impossible, he took the risk, and it succeeded. Though Dr Religa’s heart has stopped, his patient’s still beats, symbolizing medical resilience and sacrifice.
